\begin_layout Paragraph
Puzzle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Labor elasticity is important because it determines distortions introduced
 by taxes and employment response to fluctuations in productivity.
 Micro elasticity is 
\emph on
estimated
\emph default
 to be between 0 and 0.4, whereas the macro estimate 
\emph on
implies
\emph default
 an estimate between 2 to 4.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
This Paper
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Authors find that there is little relationship between micro and macro elasticit
ies of labor supply.
 This is because micro elasticities estimates only capture the intensive
 margin, whereas the macro elasticities must also capture the extensive
 margin.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prescott (AER, 2002) and others have argued that labour taxes explain a
 large share of the differences between time devoted to work in continental
 Europe versus the US (Europeans work about 70% of the US counterparts).
 People critique saying that plugging in micro labor elasticity invalidates
 Prescott's conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Research Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Are low micro labor elasticity consistent with high macro estimates?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Model of life cycle labor supply that allows micro and macro estimates of
 labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Calibrate the model to replicate features of life cycle labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Study how tax and transfer policies affect hours work in the steady-state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Key Element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-linearity in the mapping between time at work and labor services actually
 provided.
 A less important element is the heterogeneity across cohorts (young vs.
 old): productivity depends on age
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Main Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Macro elasticities are unrelated to micro elasticities â€“ micro elasticities
 in the range [0.5, 1.25] can coexist with macro elasticities in the range
 [2.25, 3].
 
\end_layout

