\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is a pseudo-summary of the literature on micro and macro labor supply
 elasticities along with a few new suggestions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Labor supply elasticity is important in understanding impact of labor tax
 on labor supply, yet there's a lot of controversy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Research Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How can we reconcile these micro vs macro views on labor supply elasticities?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey of methodologies, focusing on two main ones:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Extensive vs.
 Intensive Margins (Rogerson & Wallenius, JET 2009).
 See previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Human Capital (Imai & Keane, 2004).
 Elasticities should capture how labor supply varies with wages 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 human capital, whereas measured micro elasticities only capture how labor
 supply varies with wage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Key Element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Return to an hour of work is not only the after tax wage but also includes
 
\emph on
human capital
\emph default
 (HC), define as the expected present value of increased earnings in all
 future periods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Main Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since HC decreases with age, labor supply elasticity differs across ages.
 The tax change affects HC depending on whether it's temporary (in which
 case it does not affect HC) and it's permanent (in which case it does).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


