\end_inset


\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

SAMPLE QUESTION:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem*
In their paper 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities: A Reassessment of Conventional
 Wisdom
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (JEL 2012), Keane and Rogerson discuss two main attempts at reconciling
 the discrepacny between micro and macro elasticities.
 Briefly describe the two approaches and the key model feature that accomplishes
 the task in each.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
The authors discuss two approaches.
 The first approach, by Rogerson & Wallenius, involves a convex labor schedule
 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $e\left(a\right)\max\left\{ h-f,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $e\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is the productivity that varies with age 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the up-front cost of entering the labor market.
 This allows the agents to optimally decide to enter the market (extensive
 margin) and also decide how many hours to work (intensive margin).
 The micro elasticities only capture the intensive margin, and this mechanism
 allows the two elasticities to be virtually unrelated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The second approach, by Imai and Keane, argues that elasticities should
 capture how labor supply varies with wage 
\emph on
and 
\emph default
human capital; the measured elasticities only capture how labor supply varies
 with wage.
 In their model, the wages are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t+1}=\left(1+\kappa\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}h_{t-j}\right)w_{1}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}$
\end_inset

 represents the initial wage upon entering the market.
 In this setup, a unit increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}$
\end_inset

 raises the wage by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa w_{1}$
\end_inset

 in all future periods, so the return to an hour of work now consists of
 the after-tax wage 
\emph on
plus
\emph default
 the expected present value of increased earnings in future periods.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
