\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basic idea is that investment in standard RBC is too volatile while consumption
 too smooth.
 Introducing home production allows more substitution into and out of market
 activity in response to shocks, so it helps relieve this puzzle.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The significance of home production in economic activity has long been reocgnize
d, but its relevance for business cycle research has only been recently
 investigated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Research Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does an RBC model with home production perform? Can it improve the fact
 that investment in standard RBC is too volatile while consumption in standard
 RBC is too smooth?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce home production function into the model and expand household choices
 for allocating output.
 Then calibrate the resulting model.
 Finally, simulate the model to analyze its business cycle properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Key Element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original household choice was allocating output between consumption
 and investment; now they divide among consumption, investment in business
 capital, and investment in household capital.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Main Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incorporating home production outperforms standard RBC in matching (1) volatilit
ies of makret output, consumption and investment relative to market output,
 hours worked in the market relative to either market outpu or productivity
 and (2) correlations between investment in household and business capital.
 It still overstates the correlation between market hours & productivity
 and home & market investment.
