\begin_layout Paragraph
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Paper is motivated by two key observations that suggest that investment-specific
 technological chance may be a factor in economic growth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Over the long-run, the relative price of equipment has declined remarkably
 while the equipment-to-GNP ratio has risen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the short-run, there is a negative correlation between the price for
 equipment and equipment investment / GNP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Research Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the quantitative role of investment-specific technological change
 as an engine of growth?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Add a vintage capital model to a standard neoclassical growth model and
 matches the model to data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Key Element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Amount of equipment that can be purchased for one unit of output 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(q\right)$
\end_inset

 grows with the passage of time according to a Markov process.
 The law of motion for structures:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{s}'=\left(1-\delta_{s}\right)k_{s}+i_{s}
\]

\end_inset

is thus different from the law of motion for equipment: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{e}'=(1-\delta_{e})k_{e}+i_{e}q
\]

\end_inset

This implies that you have to investment in equipment to benefit from investment
-specific technological change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Main Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The balanced growth path shows that both the stock of equipment and new
 equipment investment grow at a higher rate than output.
 Furthermore, approximately 60% of post-war productivity growth can be attribute
d to investment-specific technological change.
 After accounting for this rapid improvement in production of capital goods,
 the productivity slowdown since the 1970s looks even worse.
